Republican leaders have justified their policy with the necessity of combating voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center calls such a fraud a myth, saying that voter fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die after being struck by lightning.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of U.S. election fraud in the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, individual states have responsibility for organizing federal elections in the U.S.
And in that spirit, most U.S. governments have been proclaiming new laws since 2009 that make the process of election or entry into the electoral list difficult.
The phenomenon saw a boom after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican representatives were added in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were submitted in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to submit photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for elections in advance, invalidate the right to register on the list of voters on the day of the election and withdraw the right to vote for citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required a photo ID on voters.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The Constitutionality of the Indiana Act was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
The Republican authorities rushed to expand this procedure to other states.
Over the past two years, they have supported drafting such laws in 34 states to force voters to present photo identity cards.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have universal identity cards, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens do not own, i.e. 21 million people of the age allowing to vote, no photo ID issued by the government office of their state.
Furthermore, it does not have such an identity card of about five million new voters in 2012.
In addition, the acquisition of the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are particularly disproportionately affected mainly by young people, members of minorities and low-income people.
Therefore, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with incomes below 35 000 dollars; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their inclination to Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who vote rather Republican candidates to use the cards issued by these clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for the election.
The first such request was introduced by Arizona.
Since 2011, about twelve states have passed laws that stipulate the duty of voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer a democratic party.
Republican legislators in 2011 backed laws in eight states that repeal the registration of voters on the day of the election.
Moreover, they have limited the right of persons and groups to provide assistance to voters who want to enroll.
These limitations have consequences.
During the 2004 general election, for example, campaigns for the registration of voters helped to register about 10 million inhabitants.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a decrease of 17% in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers then passed laws in the other five states to shorten the period for in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans accounted for 33% of voters who voted in advance, even though African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
The same was true of Hispanics.
They accounted for just 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who accounted for 76% of all voters, made up just 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic lawmakers and their supporters have strongly opposed the approval of the laws that limit voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills with their veto.
In order to suspend the validity of the most controversial laws, the U.S. Attorney General even intervened.
In part, they managed to reduce the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 countries have taken laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will make the exercise of the right to vote quite undeniably more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics speak primarily of the bias of the passed laws and see it as an obvious effort to influence the results of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states where those laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electoral corps necessary to win the presidential election.
It is too early to declare with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
