Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson sparked a legitimate stir last summer.
There is a view that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And it is also the last particle, the existence of which is predicted by the standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which, however, has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no certainty among physicists that it is a Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal, which very much resembles the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the Great Congress of Physics in Kyoto rather confirm it, but all the data is still missing so that we can be absolutely certain.
However, suppose it's a Higgs boson, because the risks of error appear to be small, and let's look at what it's all about.
In this world, there is a completely unquestionable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's excretory principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It also divides physicists into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to Pauli's principle.
And there are bosons at the other end, the wicked anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not of this principle, which means that they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: mesons, which we leave unnoticed here, and "power particles" that spread great natural forces and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as could be thought.
If you read this article, it is thanks to the boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "light particle" that is the "bearer" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to the pebble thrown into the pond.
This "disturbance" will give rise to an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "force carriers."
A more stable field
It's also with the Higgs boson, except that it's necessary to "disturb" a different field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen level of the pond, only a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the laboratory of CERN - a large hadron accelerator with accommodating beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful for us to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, for example, magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never be held by itself on the fridge.
And anyway, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let’s look at it) don’t have it.
And Mrs. Nováková asks, what is the purpose of all this research, what "they will bring us"?
From the point of view of science, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any mismatch between observations and SM predictions.
Moreover, few physicists literally want to be found, because the slightest difference could open up space for "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It is necessary to state that the model has still huge flaws, brings no clarification of gravity (oha!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic matter (again!).
However, the CERN facility has not yet discovered such contradictions.
Respondencies
The responses of these researches in the daily lives of Mr and Mrs Novák are very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
Look: at the very beginning of the 60's, the pioneers of the laser in Bell's labs had no idea of the revolution that their work would provoke.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
The physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said this - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab."
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not plan it at first, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it means that you really never know...
Palliative Care – The Best Way to Leave Life... | Le Devoir
Through his Commission on Dignified Dying, Quebec has recently become involved in a delicate end-of-life issue.
The debate should continue shortly and a bill is about to be drafted.
There is still a lot of work to be done in this crucial area.
Le Devoir magazine tried to look at this issue in more detail.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him gave him a two-year reprieve.
"They gave me five years to live and it's already seven," he says emotionlessly on his bed at the vilative care house of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"It's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The disease has done its work: immense weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet himself or to eat alone.
He looks at a tasty-looking breakfast and agrees to help him eat.
He is brave and even smiles, talks to strangers who stop by, bring him medicine, offer a bath.
Courage for ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"In all your life, you learn that men urinate standing up," Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility, recounts.
Going back to the stage of a child is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of the person" whether he accepts the return, says the psychologist.
In the opinion of a number of people engaged in palliative care, crucial moments take place at the very core of such a return.
Patients who enter the home with victor-Gadbois palliative care all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who care for them does not provide them with so-called "curative" care.
In the case of Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "on suffocation in full consciousness."
The disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good children," he adds.
"I don't have any wishes in my life anymore," she says, and then she allows us to put on her breathing apparatus.
Still, he is still looking forward to his last visit from Italy in the coming days.
In Victor-Gadbois's home, in collaboration with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
This is what palliative care looks like, if nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, one bed of palliative care per 11 700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize that we're all going to die someday.
Here, life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, it can be provided, for example, with a sip of brandy or pepsi, to taste.
Diabetics no longer have to monitor their sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
Last night they carried a beer to Mr. X, who later died last night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of the late father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," Nathalie Savard, the director of the nursing service, recounts.
In Victor-Gadbois's home, the days go one after another, but they don't resemble each other.
Alongside a ninety-three-year-old man who rejoices in his last encounter with his family thoroughly padded on his pillows while toasting in his honor, a tragically thirty-six-year-old man surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children dies after trying out all the options to survive.
"For half a year, there are always three to five beds, which are designed for people with cancer up to 45 years," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who come to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their homes, and 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care that is intended to relieve suffering once the sick arrive at the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is precisely this fundamental unavailability of healthcare in Quebec that leads to the fact that a number of doctors specializing in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of the law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been signed in circulation by peaks in the field of palliative treatment, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure all people’s access to quality palliative care before it can be agreed to carry out euthanasia.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in huge pains without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He is worried that patients will not ask for death because they are not getting appropriate care.
And at the same time, many oncologists care for their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Hélène Richard's survival hopes were minimal when she abandoned demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncoler that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was no longer fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when a team of palliative pussy relieved their pain.
However, it must be said that palliative care is definitely not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal area, patients are resisting pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives that put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether impactful or whether the sedatives are given permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient we can't get rid of pain will have an increasing opportunity to access palliative sedatives.
The sick, who are not given a sedative, always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn't always necessarily mean "I want you to give me euthanasia," it means more "I want you to relieve me of pain."
