Compared to the world exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which came out in October.
Bitcoin refers to "the most successful virtual money," "competing dollar and euro" and "the equivalent of ordinary money."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like "credits" used to advance in a video game that a person gains by playing or that can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are depositaries of the book of current accounts, controllers, issuers of money and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in fact between two electronic addresses using email.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The information file related to this transaction is electronically signed by the dual key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Furthermore, thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public current account book, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction in this book.
It is proceeded by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is the process of cutting a file; i.e., transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If the user would like to pay twice with the same money in a row (within ten minutes) for the purpose of fraud, the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into a hundred million, so the margin space is here...
The difficulty of the task is also increasing with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The used log does not apply to the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-time payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls money laundering options thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, as a WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of current accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins do not orbit.
"Huge discounts" were launched in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, is dedicated to converting bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that make it cheaper.
In addition, the carrier manages his identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up with merchants where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just tell the address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Noizat specifies, assuring that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement in questioning hierarchical systems and moving to more horizontal systems.
"Before Bitcoin asserts itself, it will take a while, but 2013 could be decisive," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB foresees a re-evaluation of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this kind of money is successful.
