Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Mohammed Morsi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants him unlimited powers, he decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else's opinion, that the Constituent Assembly will approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For nearly two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium," continues to "violate his word" and "tramples on the law."
But his supporters assure that this is a means of dealing with the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum is expected to take place in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify the article after the article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is buffeted by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the U.S. weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems confident that Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since this hurriedly organized vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I keep unlimited powers" that should otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 deputies of the aforementioned constituent assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was proclaimed, they slammed the door, saying they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights advocates, civil society or members of religious minorities have mimicked their move.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 alternates were quickly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further paused that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... hours for prayer when some members of the committee were of the opinion that the clock in the meeting room was not properly adjusted.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and provides that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental demands, hoped to replace the term "principle" with the term "rules," which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," argue liberals, who see only a rhetorical issue in it.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular on issues of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "the persons called for comment are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
The beginnings of theocracy can be seen in this.”
The concerns of the Liberals are further fueled by the fact that the university's next rector should be less moderate than the existing one.
"For now, there has been no particular religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state in the framework.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of them graduated in French schools," moderates the concerns of Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
There is especially a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to comment on it."
Yesterday's approved text is highly criticized in addition to religious pages because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction against the former regime.
Another disputed place: the powers conferred on the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Council of Defence.
Furthermore, proceedings against civilians will not be banned in military courts, as required by the human rights association.
These associations speak of their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous Constitution.
While Egypt's president was scheduled to speak in a televised address last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated salt solution are waiting for Ukrainian tourists
The promised land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the intactness of nature.
AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bowing to the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, in which Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God's mercy will descend on all who enter this "spa".
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: the transformation of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to His disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
The believers will walk the Path of Pain, or the Way of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passing through the streets of the Old Town and leading to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of crucifixion, to the stone of the anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which they made a cross for Jesus' crucifixion.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews - the Wall of Lamentations, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make the journey through the vertical
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained from a secret hiding place from the enemy that Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruin is located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who deal with mountaineering can access it on their own.
The others will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which is experiencing a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, the pagan gods reportedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit everyone in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Kumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, which were found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and approximately 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel-Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
The Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso are widely represented in its exhibition.
In Akkon you can visit the Al Basha Museum, which represents several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with mannequins of spa users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly rejected.
The Fifth Museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells of one of the most dramatic aspects of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You step inside - and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are glittering.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished are the names of the Jewish children.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
The three main spa resorts of Israel are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea you can bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not drop below 21 degrees Celsius and the air is heated up to 23 degrees.
The dead sea is even warmer, and in it people bathe all year round.
By the way, the dead sea is the most peculiar sea in the world, located at the lowest mainland point of the planet - at the level of 417 m below sea level.
Côte d'Azur water in it is a saturated saline solution that is easy to keep at the surface even for people who can't swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and medicinal mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes to cure your ruffled nerves.
Touch the mysterious past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
A glorious naval route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Indeed, tourists love wandering through narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the aisle of your "sign", luck will favor you favorably.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get a picture taken.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theatre and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully reconstructed theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, for a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
It is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is approximately 3.8 shekel).
The city's transport is mainly buses, but there is a speed tram in Jerusalem, and in the city of Haifa there is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connect the lower city with the upper one.
It's basically an underground cableway.
Traveling through all modes of urban public transport costs 6 shekels, which you can drive for 1.5 hours with the transfer.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, work ceases in marketplaces, shops and public transport.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you will only get kosher meals: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes, in which a combination of milk and meat is included.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, all kinds of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are very many fattened cats that "roam according to their taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
The leading cats love the crowded places and will eagerly embark on every goodness.
