Plus insurance - 15 dollars a day.
And renting a bike will cost around 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed by numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to get to know the country and rest.
The country was visited by the promised from January to October 2012 to 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the cancellation of visas 9. February 2011.
"Great and powerful" will announce it to Moscow: emigrants save money for language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the mandatory language exams bill, fraudsters have already emerged in the country selling "forged" certificates
13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities every year.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenia.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support families at home.
On 1 December, the law came into force, according to which every working migrant will be required to pass an examination of the knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the service, housing and municipal sectors, lifestyle and retail sales.
However, the FMS promises that in time, the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the foundation of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed to obtain and extend the work permit.
The exemption applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law is not subject to the people who successfully managed to achieve attestation and obtain an academic diploma until the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Use, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of Pushkin's Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, State University of St. St. Petersburg and other Russian universities.
Migrants can pass exams in all cities; already today, more than 160 such centers are open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by members of the State Duma and FMS (Federal Migration Services).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have been able to ask the press many times: and what will it really bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for the Russians and for the visitors themselves?
Thus, first of all - the representatives of the migration service correspond - this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering as a result of "slave labour."
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of Directors of FMS of Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights should be initiated before their departure.
Only the system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise in occupational-free emigrants, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language - he says with the conviction of Sebelev - the future migrant is condemned to clashes with rogue people who, under the pretext of help, will ensure a "vouch" for terrible, tight hostels in which he and dozens of others, like himself, will suffer for months without food and documents and work for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland, they promise one thing, but after their arrival they cheat them, confiscate their passports, do not pay their promised wages," confirms the head of the Main Tajik Labour Migration Administration, MS Tolib Sharipov.
Don't swear!
All the less so because many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get into, but do not even have experience with the work in question.
Of course, it is not so much their fault, but rather misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive at least a reasonable basic education.
After all, their families also need to feed children something, not to mention the fact that they need to be dressed, put on and equipped for school.
As children grow up to working age, they must go for work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it's hard - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, in the light of the Linguistic Testing Act, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
Testing will only be carried out on those migrants who have a legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't take exams or get any more official work.
In the meantime, most migrant workers live illegally as they used to live in Russia.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized entry prohibited"
Many of the incoming workers say that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a false registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that we have basically fake documents, without registration, and this results in cases of extortion.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Umed Hushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, shared his experience with reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy some painting"
On the first day of the law on language, it was found that not only the documents of migrants on registration were false.
FMS employees have already seized several false certificates of passing the language exam.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, in the hope that it would facilitate the problem of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
That's two and a half times the amount than passing the official test: it will cost migrating workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the immediate future is to ensure the system against corruption, so that workers cannot simply buy the documents, in which the government officials and human rights defenders agree.
Meanwhile, government authorities can promise foreign workers who failed tests the first time, the necessary time to take a course in the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active dealing with people is not required.
The Ministry of the Interior does not take the illegal arms market into circulation
The proportion of offences using legally held weapons is very low
The Ministry of the Interior of Russia presents a proposal to tighten the law in relation to owners of civilian weapons.
It is the reaction of government authorities to recent events: the stimulus was the cases of shootings at weddings that were without victims, and the massacre prepared by Moscow attorney Dimitry Vinogradov, who resulted in the deaths of seven people.
Police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and raise the age from which a gun licence can be obtained - from 18 to 21 years.
The idea is supported by the head of the Committee on Security and the Fight against Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, who has promised that changes to the Arms Act will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian state authorities are trying to deal with the problem by "tightening the screws."
An open letter has appeared on the network, whose authors - representatives of various social shooting organizations - demand the rejection of the "senseless tightening" of the law.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, said Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and criminalist, in an interview with the Russian BBC editorial board.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, in the six months of 2012 there were committed 142 crimes from the use of firearms registered by the authorities of the Ministry of the Interior, while over the same period a total of 1168 thousand crimes were committed.
The authors of the open letter are convinced, tightening civil gun legislation will not prompt the perpetrators to switch to a "black" market.
According to them, it is currently possible to find any weapon in Moscow at a low price.
Currently, the Interior Ministry says the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from plants to officers
The "Black" arms market is supplied with several channels.
The main channels are five, says retired colonel Victor Baranec, who worked for ten years in the workplaces of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of sites that accept gun orders
The first - an "army or military route," that is, a weapon that was stolen during fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were also stolen by Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranec.
Another type of "black guns" are guns stolen by criminals from security forces officials.
Baranec explains that this includes thefts from police warehouses and weapons stolen directly from employees of law enforcement agencies.
Illegal "mainly" goes on sale from military warehouses.
In many military warehouses, explosions often occur.
"It is proven that some of the fires were started intentionally - to cover up the manka," the former soldier says.
According to Barance, the gun manufacturers also make their contribution.
"At present, private arms companies that are not competitive in the international market are being created and are decommissioning weapons that supply the black market, including Moscow," the expert says.
Another source of the "black" market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of pistols and vending machines come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is their production, sometimes the weapons are produced in small-scale production, and a mafia was created that organized their continuous production," explains the former soldier.
Where's the gun from?
Experts have added up what is the approximate share of individual sources of supply of illegal weapons to the "black" market.
The report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Design.
The specialists analyzed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and the Russian Statistical Office, criminological literature and data of public data portals focused on the topic of weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, researchers say, come from military and executive bodies.
Half of all weapons have found themselves on the black market "due to officials whose work is linked to weapons," the report said.
