In simple terms, European legislation regulates how to deal with public procurement, followed by individual national legislation and then by practice itself.
We have put all of this together, and although the control is not yet complete, we have shown very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps even "stricter and more perfect" in our country, but the practice itself is better in Germany in some parameters.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create ever more precise rules, but it is necessary to devote yourself to the application of the law itself.
What can this project help you with, what does it mean for you?
Such joint control could contribute to stopping the effort to refine the law, lowering and improving the limits when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economics means getting the right thing to do for a reasonable (but that does not always mean the lowest) price in order to exclude enrichment and possibly criminal conduct.
But by lowering the order limit, we don't necessarily have to achieve that.
Maybe the system will become so crowded with "paper" that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw them much more easily from it than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transposition of legislation on public procurement into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is the office similar to our SAO here, or is it set differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, as the SAO operates there Bundesrechnungshof, which is organized similarly to us, also has a college, only it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities proceed similarly.
The powers are also similar to some extent, but by the fact that Germany has a federal arrangement, so it has these courts at the level of individual Länder - in this the system is a little different from ours.
BRH can only control federal money, represented by state resources in our country.
Public funds, which are managed by the region and municipalities, are controlled there from the level of the Federal Courts of Auditors.
As for the legislation, it is easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, but in some respects Germany is referred to as a model, but it cannot be said that it is better at everything.
Is it because they have better controllers?
I certainly don't, but I say again, I don't like that kind of comparison.
But it has to be said that even countries that we consider a role model are facing a number of problems.
Otherwise, it would be of no benefit to them to cooperate with our office, wouldn't it?
As for the domestic legislation, what the amendment to the Public Procurement Act meant for your office, are its effects already manifested in some way?
Due to the fact that the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet reflected in the auditing actions.
Because we do ex-post checks, we need to take into account some delays.
We are only observing this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have started our new tool "detection of the risks of inefficientness", through which we have run almost 14 thousand public contracts, and we have analyzed them - there, of course, those changes will manifest themselves, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tender will be adjusted, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law rather as a benefit, or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracies?
I think this bill is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will "tighten" and it will not be possible to follow them.
Already with the operation of the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a violation of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth tightening the law in this way?
Not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on bureaucracy.
So how do you get out of it?
Let's see where the road doesn't go.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs by checking that so-called "svartssystem" - and what does that mean?
Is the Švarcsystem prohibited or permitted?
After all, the law must be set up somehow, and if it bans something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activities of the office, which is obliged to go to control and enforce duties.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it," but it can't say we're going to do like nothing.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on what is to be formally done - which is right to protect public tender.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when a bidder with the best offer is excluded only for formal deficiencies.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be the right application - that's what I think is missing from us.
