Šimon Ornest: At concerts, we want to accumulate positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
It's just one of the other alarm messages that we humans like to catch.
Together with the band The Tap Tap, we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also organize a unique project three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce him to the readers?
It's a national benefit event that we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on December 20, from 21 o'clock, 3 concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end around the time the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific, which is in the time zone 12 hours ahead.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally it was probably my idea, then we invented everything together with our artist Honza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to accumulate enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think with the public about the state in which we will one day pass this world on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items of shoes, T-shirts, bags or original keys against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing at www.e-tap.cz.
The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is called "The End of the World Canceled."
She is already very popular on YouTube today, will she also hear at these benefit concerts?
Of course, in the very end, if we succeed and the end of the world does not come...
It will be sung by all performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
The anthems will also suddenly connect in a unique live stream on Czech Television.
He wrote the words about this song and the main role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, Xindl X also sings in it...
How did you get into cooperation with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, due to the fact that we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We try to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turns out that most of them are interested and entertained by cooperation with us.
What will the proceeds from concerts against the end of the world go to?
On the equipment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we have been implementing for the sixth year with the civic association Tap in the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute school regularly run out of lecturers and engage in activities that entertain and interest them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to allow them to do so in this way.
Within the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be built in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
How did you choose them?
We tried to put together a program that will appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar “bombastic events” for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so we will definitely prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play in the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, when we are in the USA, I would like to connect it with a performance in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, so far you have performed, for example, in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group that consists of handicapped people.
How do you manage these paths logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
We have five members on an electric wheelchair, her trolleys have to travel in the luggage compartment, further, of course, we carry a large number of cargo and boxes with tools...
However, so far it has always been done without problems, both CSA and British Airways were well prepared for us, that I was surprised how many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how individuals differ in barrier-freeness, public access to handicapped and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than in our country, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything in the east is still in the very beginning.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-winging, here it is still unusual for a person to move on an electric wheelchair himself in the city center.
There are not even such obvious things, as that, for example, wheelchair users prefer in the elevator.
Fortunately, civic associations are already being established there, which are trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we still have to catch up with more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're still behind...
However, it is important to mention that improving and improving the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in which, on the contrary, we are a little ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or barrier-free is one thing, but only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers, will things really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The band The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but let’s go back a few years ago, what made you want to start it in 1998?
I joined the Jedlička Institute as an educator, where I had many young people around me who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play, among other things, on the saxophone, so together with a colleague I founded a hobby music club.
Well, over time, as our presenter Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
But the popularity came only in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with well-known singers and also actively work to promote the band.
We realized that a job that is not visible, basically as if it didn't exist.
Thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can also afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was your goal to make it with The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something different.
Show business is crowded with things where one imitates the other.
It is logical in a way, everything new is accepted carefully and it takes a long time.
The things that are unique are very few, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, that is natural...
But that regret is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not suffering from all abandoned beings that we have to regret.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary resources to do so.
I say that if something succeeds with people with disabilities, it is not just a shift for them, but for the whole society.
Did it also help that success that you are a strict boss, as many people have labeled you?
When we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and require some discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and a head in the clouds, and when they find that they have to go to the rehearsal twice a week, go to the product and spend a lot of time on the road to concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
The band The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were at the beginning of 1998?
Only one Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people leave and come, that can't be prevented.
Whoever has the will and the taste always has the door open with us
