Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, Poland was accepted as a member of the European Space Agency as the twenty-first member of the European Space Agency, the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of agency projects over the following years.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had been involved in flights to space before the Second World War; but they did not always meet with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of lecture A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work, the Entry into Space.
The Ideas of a Young Engineer (b. 1905) left the listener cold and after years of Šternfeld remembered that only dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelteri and André Louis Hirsch Award for his entry into spacecraft in France.
The remembered doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and space.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous space promoter, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925, a rail dress was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dressage or to brake it.
Information about this dressage is known only from the contemporary press.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to deal with missiles.
The research was provided by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegim.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research reached the stage of practical examinations.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter missile, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work of Rakieto - torpedo powietrzna and the rakietobomb of the lotnicza author Leliwa-Krzywoblocké was published.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects of military use of missile technology were dedicated to the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activities ceased the start of the war.
Other works devoted to spacecraft appear after the war in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Towarzystwo Astronautyczne.
The first mention is in the November issue of the 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, in which there are four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from prof. M. Subotowicz, is proposed the creation of a company that will deal with spacecraft.
At that time, the projects of artificial satellites were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaus Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn, PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish missile to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start was 10. October 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-rise wind.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, a 0.4-litre space, a 0.34-litre Meteor-1B and a 0.62-litre Meteor-1C were available.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of around 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Poland also participated in the research of outer space on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in public.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in a globalised world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic departments, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
The cause is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labour, (wages) there is a price tension.
Under this term, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the producer tries to compete by importing cheap goods by "undermining" the price of a competitor in order to tear down a greater market share and thereby increasing its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means either translating production abroad for most entrepreneurs, or buying cheaply there, or disappearing.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus a responsibility for the unemployment produced by it, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is enhanced by the complete unwillingness of the masters of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social and social damages caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so widely known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into competition with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital their own population regardless of social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force the population to adopt the price dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and by limiting the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is growing poverty, along with an increase in the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, there have been public food dispensaries for the poor for many years, who cannot make a living from their own work.
The number of these people is already going into the millions.
In order to increase the competitiveness of the German economy, there are quite commonly cases where properly employed people receive such a wage that the state must pay them an existential minimum.
Such a scandal was also published in the case of the auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation when people under the pressure of a disastrous decline in the social level are forced to either emigrate as was the case in the 19th century or live on hungry wages on the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital will perhaps come to the country someday.
But here it is necessary to ask where it will come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because the Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, or Turk, Moroccan, or Egyptian, or African still work for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
The liberal theory and the media, until they are tired, argue that the state cannot participate capitalically in its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital insists that the State must not interfere with the economy through management interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not affect, now it actually governs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the clear answer that it is.
The proof is the existence of a virtually all-powerful and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, the provision of mutual advantages, legislation, where practically everything is reprehensible, but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is that the state ministries, for lack of funds, enter the drafting of bills to private legal firms that are heavily related to industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power thus comes not from the people as proclaimed by Western-type constitutions, but from financially strong groups preferring their own interests.
Clearly, liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly getting into a situation, as described by Appianos in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in complete disarray, and the authorities have occupied themselves with violence.
For bribes, unlawful acquisition of favor and with the help of stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant without any inhibitions, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold voice" ..."characteristic people did not apply for the office at all, so once, as a result of this disruption, the state was without consuls for eight months". “It has indeed begun to be said that the only medicine in a bad situation is self-government, and that an energetic man must be chosen.” Appiános thought of Pompey, but it was Caesar who turned democracy into self-government.
Conclusion As in antiquity, contemporary society is based on a reckless preference for its own benefit regardless of society-wide interest.
Private capital is by its very nature unable to understand and apply society-wide benefit.
The result is now, as is then, the unprecedented decadence of elites without any effort to reform a deeper nature.
The causality of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the reckless liberalization of 19th and 20th century economic systems.
Under the current situation, the demise of these systems in favour of a liberal-type democracy can be considered a certain break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that the current elites are completely ignoring in the future the possible hundreds of thousands of lives, humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing along with crimes against humanity as we know them from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not permanent.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and internal European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political-social reforms that will strengthen the capital participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
