Argo: When the worst is to call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and captured 52 diplomats as hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlavi, who fled to the U.S. after the revolution, which had been the patron saint of his regime for several decades.
For the U.S. administration, the situation did not offer a positive way out - throwing the Shah overboard could not afford, because it would so fundamentally jeopardize trust in allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was unable to achieve.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later exacerbated by the fiasco of an attempt to free the hostages by force.
The jailed diplomats were eventually released after 444 days after the Algerian government brokered the negotiations.
Their lot at home sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film by director Ben Affleck Argo describes one episode of that history that brought America a minor victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees escaped from it.
After complex peripates, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went to Canadian passports as members of the film crew, who in the country surveyed the locations for the shooting of a big-fined sci-fi movie.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the legend credible, it was written about a film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece, a betrayal - an example of this is the Danny's partnering series.
The film alternates moods - on the one hand, documentary sequences from Tehran (in the subtitle sequence are shown iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, light passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - the men in the suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, in the telephone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable reboot of his career.
The mock actor became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime of Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film, not taking place in the director's hometown of Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that the director's older films exalted above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck is also showing it in Argo, where Tehran is "playing" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotion of confusion and unpredictability that occur when history moves out of nowhere.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in scenes fictional (fake crew at the Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not offer much in the film sense of thrilling scenes.
She almost works with it quite successfully, sometimes she thinks something about reality - everything doesn't work out so elegantly there anymore (the scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport turns away a phone call in America and the chase after the runway looks pretty far-fetched).
But the weakness of Argo is distraction resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film somewhat loses its dramatic turn, it's a film that can be watched with mild interest, appreciate the realization and retro style evoking thrillers of the 70's.
But it's hard to pull.
As a reminder of one still living history, as well as a testament to how exaggerated the notions of the all-powerful and all-knowing secret services are, but sufficient.
