Spijkenisse, a housing estate in close proximity to Rotterdam without its own job opportunities, which is not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
This municipality with 80 000 inhabitants has the lowest level of education in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to resolve this stupid situation, several years ago, the decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges depicted on euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councillors recognized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, a master of insanely bold bar charts and a contractor of funny, often even cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calm, and at a competition meeting in 2003 he appeared with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in stunny and shrugging its shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled his gifts on top of each other according to size and ended his activistly reasoned speech with the words "Dear towns!"
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was piled up for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
The small-town grey, which has not yet been able to offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is, thanks to this, richer in a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural structure in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: a reading eldorado under a cheese hatch.
The resort of the mountain mass is the elevator, but you will discover real spatial and reading passions only when you walk topography.
From all sides the glass interior is bright and clear, the floor of a burnt cabin and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, there are shelves with books along the facade and in the middle there is a large dark space that is mostly incozy and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and we ejected the space for the reader from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is cleverly used: on Wednesday there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a control panel of house technology.
A special delight is the black shelves for books, which are once the lining of the walls, once the windowsill and other times the railing of the stairs.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads over unknown building material.
"We wanted to work here with recycled materials," says Joop Trouborst, head of the project at the municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
And so, in one of the Friesian farms, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture one day.
For many years, a millimeter fleece of synthetic matter has been used as a base under the roots of greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons and then is ripe to throw away in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantity - was pressed onto a plate with a thickness of four centimetres.
The effect of heat and pressure turns so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you will reach the top.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter-long journey, you will be rewarded in a literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and ficuls in pots.
They take care of the atmosphere, but mainly the correct humidity in the mountains of literature.
