It heats up and cools with the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass hatch, the sun shines in only briefly, even on sunny days.
The wide glued wooden trusses, which stand perpendicular to the glass facade, serve as a shading and capture a large part of the sun's radiation.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest can handle fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial IT business skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to Boekenberg as the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
Thus, optical gaps in the previously not fully equipped library, which currently consists of 70 000 pieces, should be filled.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are completely full.
"There's nothing worse than a half-declised library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
This is how MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated.
This is ultimately the starting point for identity.
