But some scientists and experts on children's development are increasingly coming with praise for boredom.
They say that it is good for us (and our children) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can promote creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we don't have a chance to enjoy the boredom.
Should we encourage boredom?
Yes. Yes.
And no.
But I'll get back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom is a relatively new phenomenon that has occurred with the arrival of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the Canadian University of Calgary, who is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011), says.
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls in Pompeii was found a Latin inscription related to boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then the question is how we define boredom.
The trouble is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, John D said. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After watching the research literature and showing the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I wasn't able to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy by the fact that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no urge to do anything about apathy.
He says the core of boredom is "a violation of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and a feeling of slowly passing time."
Boredom can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when we're just having trouble concentrating.
In his study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," which was published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read an article from a journal.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they could barely notice it, while the third group could not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but they were not sure why and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When you're trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, a distraction can lead to boredom, Mark J said. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you do something boring, "like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and doodling, which is often viewed as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom to fight and keep people physically more attentive.
"The research shows that children who are allowed to be wagged will learn more and retain more information than those forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We've all experienced boredom sometimes - the delay of my flight, the humming speaker, the particularly lengthy movie.
But some individuals have a better chance of getting bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists in the 1980s developed a "Scale for Susceptibility to Boredom Proneness Scale."
The scale includes questions like, "A lot of things I have to do are repeated and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodnovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
However, teenagers are generally indifferent.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren't in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knew that "adolescence is a peak time for boredom," which is largely due to the fact that children and youth are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: "Is boredom good for you?"
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, play gambling, or abuse addictive substances as a way to mitigate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers discussed the link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodnovich, who has studied the issue for more than two decades.
"Boredom is a way of brain to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the most appropriate thing you should do.
If you're bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won't be bored anymore, but he won't learn how to have fun or self-administer, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate procedure is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of our reach of constant thornying of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We accuse her of the need to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be associated with something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy their free time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly over-stimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise shuts down."
