The hardest craft in the world: sulphur carriers in the Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, carriers in the Indonesian volcano are gambling with their lives and health as they endure 70 kilos of sulphur down steep stone trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anta Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living by conquering the sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, every day must rise to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gases escape from the interior of the Earth and, when in contact with the air, pass to a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulphur that weigh up to 70 kilos together, it carries them on the shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone trails.
To the top of the volcano, which towers 2 386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but it takes more than 40 minutes for the exhausted carriers to climb upwards at a turtle pace, as they maintain balance and thoroughly deliberate their steps so that they do not slip and crash into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to one French tourist who crashed from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for each kilo of sulfur they mine
When they're up, they make their way around the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 metres.
It is the firm PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has benefited in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10 000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even sugar bleaching.
"Because we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46 000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," Anto explains to us, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and at the end he is destroyed, but he can earn 138 000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
While this seems like a negligible amount for such an inhumane effort, it's three times what he would make in the field.
"The daily salary of the miners here is very high. For example, coffee is collected with 15 000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier, which previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75 000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, has trouble breathing, still coughs, and his eyes are irritated with toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks living in a Kawah Ijen volcano three times a day, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him, despite having a face protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated with toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than decent English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man, afflicted by fate, could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at a hotel, and instead does the work of a carrier.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and wakes up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because the sulfur at night continues to spring up and its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
