About 400 carriers carry on the shoulders of a basket with sulfur from the bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, has not mechanized the sulphur extraction due to cost savings, nor does it provide carriers working on their own and with such effort, no equipment.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of the 30 000 rupees (2.5 euros) from the surcharge for photography, which, along with a ticket for 15 000 rupees (1.2 euros), are collected by the nature park’s guards from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for cattle, and not for people," argues Madrusin, a sturdy 42-year-old carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left schools.
He manages to lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he can work "as long as possible" because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings in the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and traps the miners in the dense vapors that come out of the volcano, the miners are so claiming that none of them complain that they suffer from serious illnesses... but it is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and wounds on the shoulders caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulphur in a volcano, which then take three trucks down a steep road between the thickets to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, missing several teeth.
Of his five sons, the oldest, thirty-year-old, also earns by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the world's heaviest crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the fact that they do not have children, careers, stress and the cost of living and education.
"The population of Singapore needs growth."
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot. Let us do our civic duty and beget a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol candy ad, but still - or perhaps for that very reason - the video expanded mass-wide to YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These sentences are part of rap, which uses local allusions like "we put a bun in the oven" as a mockery of the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a funny way.
Douglas Hamilton, the agency's artistic director, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people fulfill "their civic duty."
"This is exclusively an issue of the Internet, so it must have been funny and funny.
It's the country's biggest problem.
We are the worst in the world in the reproduction of our population, so we felt that this was a topic that we had to touch on.
We knew the government was trying to do a lot of things like spread perfumes with pheromons or organize dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like the composition of rap, to solve this problem.”
1.2 children
He who doesn't take it too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend USD 1 300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
However, all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city-state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for its representatives' conservatism and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore with regard to the stratification of the population is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded the value was 2, which is considered the recovery rate, in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the National Government's Department of Marriage and Family Affairs, says it's because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"People thus have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, it's not just a wedding and a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increasing the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbearing. The result is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
While immigration policy efforts have been made to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as measures against population decline, this has caused displeasure among locals.
On some Singaporean websites, undisguised xenophobia is seen against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping salaries low and little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year the Singapore government party recorded its worst election result since independence began.
After the election, there was an effort to solve the problem with quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has known impacts on national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development has begun regulating the number of small apartments known as "boot boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in the marketability.
However, there is concern that these apartments can support a bachelor's lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family houses.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of developer EL Developers, claims their "shoeboxes" are selling far faster than larger homes.
"They are more popular, by selling for days to weeks faster than houses with a larger size.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow.'
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could aim to increase the birth rate of the nation, the interview with Singaporeans working in a financial district in the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, just like education, that's why a lot of people put it off," says a young official.
"Let the others have children.
But for me, it's important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about twenty-year-old, youngster.
Both men and women mention career, stress and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who have the final say about starting a family.
What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something that has a personal nature or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any violation."
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet matters that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 who are frequent internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely inherent" on a personal level and a "user name and password" when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my biggest secret," says ten-year-old Jorge in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has accounts for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she argues.
"On FB I give nice photos or photos of us playing.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wouldn't be mine, or a photo that would ridicule anyone," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, photos of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine supporters on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I opened a Twitter account so I could express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicating with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of fourteen-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits to the last network that he doesn't know 20 people from his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them directed him to anything, nor did he ask for an address or phone number.
"If they urged me or demanded it from me, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to the experience of what is now called cyberbullying.
"They blackmailed a friend on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who he was," he confirms.
The victim, according to Jose, did not opt out of the account.
"She's just activated the private regime."
Then he explains a series of steps on how to secure the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he argues.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that children and adolescents need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
It states that: "The Internet was created as a means of searching for information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic fellow Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Aborigines and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are still learning for ourselves.”
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also, to be - in terms of the surroundings - deliberate, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing this on the Internet?
Or: Would you like it if someone posted your photo the way you posted your friend's?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you tag people in the photos from the celebrations, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more: Do everyone constantly need to know what you're doing?
The next point is to realize that they have to behave in the same way in the Internet environment as outside it.
It's the same rules.
"One is guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and it should be the same on social media," he argues.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-grade teacher and education counselor explains that it is essential for children's parents to read the rules of social networks carefully.
"If they understand every insidiousness, they have a good basis to talk to children about the consequences that setting up an account on the Internet can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to share or publish," he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers."
The summit of South America is over and the Lima statement has not been made public
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today ended without issuing a statement from Lima, which was announced and which was reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access a document signed at the sixth meeting of Unasur's heads of state and government, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the presidential office, who initially determined to publish the document after the summit, said it would be later published on the Peruvian government's website.
They further said the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists have had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video from the presidential assembly was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "confidential session, transmission of sound prevented."
A small amount of the information available to journalists was provided by the press secretaries of some governments who were present, but not by a Peruvian spokesman.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, prompting the displeasure of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is just a statement from President Humala, and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and the originally promised Lima Declaration was not made public on this occasion, despite being zealously required by the press.
On the official ASPA website, it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasts for all journalists, but to completely prevent the flow of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the dispute over the border between the two countries.
Peru President Ollanta Humala and Chile's President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin on Monday by hearing the defense speech of both sides to discuss a dispute launched by Lima against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute the judgment that will resolve the dispute we are hearing in this international court today," President Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country respecting international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, conventions and international courts," Piñera added, greeting President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that he would submit to the decision of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, thus expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime border with Nicaragua, and Colombia deemed the decision to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chavez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from the organization Unasur in 2011 after the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening morning speeches and ending the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read the final document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been accepted and that 31 projects had been planned between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries would take "important steps towards a South American citizenship target for which residence agreements are being expanded."
He said actions were encouraged to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a victorious essence, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our peoples a better future.”
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport links of various places of South America, especially rural and border areas... to make our countries more connected and create new economic ties," the Peruvian president said in a reading.
He mentioned that five of these projects relate to Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two relate to a better connection with Ecuador, but did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return to the Union of South American Nations” from which it is currently excluded.
Another of the issues highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful area that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In that sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before his participation in the regional meeting that he hopes to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to respect the International Court of Justice's ruling on the dispute over the maritime border, which is disputed by Bogota.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will discuss all the solutions, none are excluded, nor a treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega to lead the negotiations in the most civilized and thoughtful possible form," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peñi Nieta.
As part of the summit, the EU's defence ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and a consensus on defence of the field.
The members of UNASUR are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the last mentioned country is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chairman of the regional bloc.
