The head of Ecuadorian state attended the sixth summit of the Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) today, which concluded with calls for greater regional integration in order to maintain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims are now the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was like lightning hit me," he recounts in his memory of the moment of truth, which the doctor tried to "relieve a little" but apparently to no avail.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his own illness on his own shoulders and began to report on it. And that's with such a commitment that he's already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is without a doubt one of the most ancient HIV patients of the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio lives with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) from the age of 22, which was something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options and greater stigma.
Even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are a lot of people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused destruction of the organism and has debilitated the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS has emerged in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "means great success that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate way is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, adding that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that the researchers concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that survival and full-life depend on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, with better those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 cells CD4 to 50 years.
Simply put, it means that whoever is diagnosed with HIV at 25 can, according to these findings, "in adherence to treatment to live without problems until the age of 75," the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the death rate has decreased significantly in recent years and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has fallen from 6 678 in 2007 to 4 862 in 2011 (UN/AIDS Joint Programme Yearbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and so far by May this year, 187. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured.
- Why do people continue to die from the disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
In the last 12 years, we have not exhausted our medical supplies. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they do not know the condition of the infection, i.e. in the late stage of the disease."
He adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when some associated infection already manifests. The only thing that needs to be done in order to be able to influence overall mortality more is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore it is necessary to offer large-scale tests to detect the disease to all those who ask for it."
In his proposal, he coincides with specialists and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in the state of Jalisco, and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to get tests done in a private laboratory just because his friend did it, and despite his young age, AIDS has already broken out and also suffered from Kaposi sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather have a lot of fun three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthy, I exercise, I take medication.”
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
“I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I pay attention to myself and the other person," Fabrizio, who has accepted the invitation to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today as part of World AIDS Day.
"Let them have the tests done. If they took a risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, it's better. And if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message summarizes the motto of the Battle against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a large gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajar journalist who finds out information about HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that are dedicated to this task "they have actually increased the distribution of condoms, they used to give us one or two, today they give us packages even hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most susceptible to the new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question full of irony and judging from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and medical staff that teens want to avoid, the reporter says.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution. Let the condoms not just be behind the counters, but let the hundred be found in dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"It's not a promiscuity boost.
Nor is it about "paying them beer and motel," as Governor Emilio González reacted to a question about whether he would agree to distribute condoms in his county.
There is no such sexuality. It is best to make condoms accessible to those who already lead the sex life," he noted.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
There were 13 435 cases (12 158 cases of AIDS and 1 317 cases of HIV).
This condition marks the fourth place in new and detected cases of AIDS in Mexico and 13th place in connection with HIV.
92% of the infection occurs sexually, 6% bloodstream y 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50 thousand people can live with HIV, because for one registered case there are four to five people who do not know about the disease.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognize the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt established by bankruptcy in Mexico, raises a detrimental precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
So it seems that the restructuring procedures of companies that allow Mexican law do not apply in the country of stripes and stars despite international agreements.
Approval of the judgment issued 15. Last June, Judge Harlin Hal, in bankruptcy court for northern Texas, left Mexican firms in practice defenseless against the possibility of confiscating their property on the other side of the el Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to the U.S. Supreme Court of Mexico to the main glassmaker, appealing against three irregularities.
First of all, while a judge of this case argues that creditors are to be governed by the United States Insolvency Act, the Fifth District Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says the main procedure is determined by bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, this would indicate ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Essentially, a model law of the United Nations was created for this purpose to unify international commercial law, which is designated by the Arbitrator by the American Law Institute.
Secondly, the judgment stipulates that without a vote of branches from the internal corporate structure, when the debt of the parent company Vitro vs. branches is recognised, the required majority would not be achieved for the approval of the restructuring.
However, Mexican laws allow this possibility.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples of Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose internal debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
In addition, it is true that even after deducting the votes of the branches, creditors - who opposed Vitro would stand trial in the United States, i.e. funds of "vultures" such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not reach a majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37.
This figure is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From a different point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of a serious economic crisis that struck the United States.
Meanwhile, the family firm Gonzáleze Sady will appeal for a new assessment directly before the Court of Appeal to make the assessment with full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, because only three had originally voted.
